  <section id="history">
    <h2>Company Background</h2>
    <p>Canva was founded in 2013 by Melanie Perkins (CEO), Cliff Obrecht (COO), and Cameron Adams (CPO) in Sydney, Australia. Perkins and Obrecht previously founded Fusion Books, a yearbook design platform, which provided the technical foundation for Canva's template-based approach. The company has raised over $560 million in funding from investors including Sequoia Capital, Blackbird Ventures, and Felicis Ventures, reaching a valuation of approximately $40 billion.</p>

    <h3>Market Position &amp; Growth</h3>
    <p>Canva's growth trajectory is remarkable: from 10 million MAU in 2017 to 230+ million in 2026. The platform claims 31+ million paid subscribers. Annual recurring revenue reportedly exceeded $4 billion in 2025. The acquisition of Affinity (professional design suite) in 2026 and making it free represented a direct challenge to Adobe's Creative Cloud monopoly, as it gave every Canva user access to professional-grade photo editing, vector design, and publishing tools at no additional cost.</p>

    <h3>Affiliate Program</h3>
    <p>Canva operates the "Canvassador" affiliate program through Impact.com. Commissions are a flat bounty per qualified Pro subscriber: approximately $36 for an annual Pro sign-up or $20.78 for a monthly Pro. The program uses 30-day cookie tracking (last-click attribution). Application is through canva.com/affiliates. Canva manages 9,000+ global referral partners through its Impact.com partnership cloud.</p>

    <h3>AI Strategy</h3>
    <p>Canva's AI strategy is distinct from pure AI companies: rather than developing a single best-in-class AI model, Canva builds an orchestration layer that routes user requests to the best available model for each task. This allows Canva to partner with multiple AI providers (OpenAI, Google, Runway, Leonardo.AI, Stability AI) and swap underlying models without changing the user interface. The "Canva Shield" safety layer is positioned as a competitive advantage over standalone AI tools that lack integrated content policy enforcement.</p>
  </section>

  <section id="recommend">
    <h2>Who Should Use Canva AI?</h2>
    <h3>Best For</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Content creators and bloggers</strong> who produce social graphics, blog thumbnails, and presentation assets and want AI shortcuts without leaving their design tool.</li>
      <li><strong>Affiliate marketers</strong> who need branded content across multiple platforms and formats — Magic Resize and Bulk Create alone save hours per week.</li>
      <li><strong>Small business owners</strong> who need professional-looking marketing materials without hiring a designer and want the simplest possible AI integration.</li>
      <li><strong>Social media managers</strong> producing 20-30 graphics per week — Bulk Create, Magic Design, and social scheduling are directly in your workflow.</li>
      <li><strong>Freelancers</strong> who want one subscription for design, AI, and stock assets instead of piecing together multiple tools.</li>
      <li><strong>Non-designers</strong> who need passable visuals and find dedicated AI tools intimidating or expensive — Canva AI is the most accessible entry point.</li>
    </ul>
    <h3>Skip If</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>You need <strong>best-in-class AI image generation</strong> at the quality of Midjourney or DALL-E 3 — Dream Lab is good but not at that level.</li>
      <li>You require <strong>fine-grained control over AI parameters</strong> that only dedicated tools provide (negative prompting, style weights, CFG scale, seed control).</li>
      <li>You're a <strong>professional designer</strong> doing colour-managed prepress, complex motion graphics, or Adobe-native client handoffs.</li>
      <li>You produce <strong>exclusively long-form written content</strong> and don't need design features — a dedicated AI writing tool would serve you better for less.</li>
      <li>You want <strong>unlimited free AI usage</strong> — the Free plan's 200 AI uses/month is fine for testing but insufficient for regular content production.</li>
      <li>You need <strong>a single-user tool your colleague can also use</strong> — Pro is one-person only; sharing requires Business at $20/seat/mo.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

